p2.text:
For the purposes of this Act:

- a) a „road user“ is anyone who directly participates in road traffic;

- b) a „vehicle operator“ is the owner of a vehicle or another natural or legal person authorized by the owner to operate the vehicle in their own name;

- c) an „escort of led or driven animals“ is a road user who accompanies animals walking individually or in herds on a road; a pedestrian leading a dog is not an escort of led or driven animals;

- d) a „driver“ is a road user who drives a motor or non-motor vehicle or a tram; a rider on an animal is also a driver;

- e) a „carter“ is a driver who drives an animal-drawn vehicle;

- f) a „vehicle“ is a motor vehicle, a non-motor vehicle, or a tram;

- g) a „motor vehicle“ is a non-rail vehicle powered by its own propulsion unit and a trolleybus;

- h) a „non-motor vehicle“ is a vehicle moving by human or animal power, such as a bicycle, handcart, or animal-drawn vehicle;

- i) a „vehicle combination“ is a combination consisting of one or more motor vehicles and one or more trailers;^2)

- j) a „pedestrian“ also includes a person pushing or pulling a sled, a pram, a wheelchair, or a handcart with an overall width not exceeding 600 mm, moving on skis or roller skates, or by means of a manual or motorized wheelchair, leading a bicycle, a motorcycle with a cylinder volume up to 50 cm^3, a dog, and the like;

- k) a „public transport vehicle“ is a bus, trolleybus, or tram;

- l) „not to endanger“ means the driver's duty to act in such a way that no danger arises for another road user;

- m) „not to restrict“ means the driver's duty to act in such a way that they do not obstruct another road user in any way;

- n) „to stand“ means to bring a vehicle to rest for a period exceeding the time allowed for stopping;

- o) „to stop“ means to bring a vehicle to rest for the time strictly necessary for the immediate boarding or alighting of transported persons or for the immediate loading or unloading of cargo;

- p) „to stop a vehicle“ means to interrupt driving due to a reason independent of the driver's will;

- q) „to give way“ means the driver's duty not to start driving or a driving maneuver or not to continue with them if the driver who has the right of way would have to suddenly change direction or speed of travel;

- r) a „motorway“ is a road marked with the traffic sign „Motorway“;

- s) a „motorway for motor vehicles“ is a road marked with the traffic sign „Motorway for motor vehicles“;

- t) a „traffic lane“ is a part of the roadway allowing the passage of vehicles other than two-wheeled vehicles (motorcycles) in a single traffic stream one behind the other;

- u) an „acceleration lane“ is an auxiliary traffic lane intended for vehicles to merge into the through lane's traffic stream;

- v) a „shoulder“ is a part of the road surface lying between the edge of the adjacent traffic lane and the edge of the road crown,^1) usually consisting of a paved and an unpaved part;

- w) an „intersection“ is a place where roads intersect or meet; the outlet of a field or forest road or another access road onto another road of a higher category is not considered an intersection;

- x) the „intersection boundary“ is a place marked by the horizontal traffic sign „Continuous transverse line“, „Continuous transverse line with the symbol Give Way!“ or „Continuous transverse line with the inscription STOP“; where such a traffic sign is not present, the intersection boundary is formed by a perpendicular to the axis of the roadway at the point where the curvature of the edge of the roadway begins for the intersection;

- y) a „controlled intersection“ is an intersection where traffic is controlled by light signals, possibly accompanied by acoustic signals, or by a uniformed police officer (hereinafter referred to as „police officer“), a uniformed military police officer (hereinafter referred to as „military police officer“);

- z) a „through lane“ is a traffic lane continuing in the original direction (without turning) through an intersection or at a place where the number of traffic lanes changes;

- aa) a „tram lane“ is a part of the road primarily intended for tram traffic;

- bb) a „railway crossing“ is a place where a road crosses a railway, or another track located on a separate body, at grade, and marked with the appropriate traffic sign;

- cc) a „municipality“ is a built-up area whose beginning and end are marked on the road by appropriate traffic signs; signs are not installed on access roads;

- dd) a „pedestrian crossing“ is a place on a road intended for pedestrians to cross, marked by the appropriate traffic sign;

- ee) a „road obstruction“ is anything that could endanger the safety or smooth flow of road traffic, such as cargo, material or other objects, a vehicle left on the road, or defects in the road's passability;

- ff) „reduced visibility“ is a situation where road users cannot sufficiently clearly distinguish other vehicles, persons, animals, or objects on the road, for example, from dusk to dawn, in fog, snowfall, heavy rain, or in a tunnel;

- gg) an „identity document“ is a document by which a citizen of the Czech Republic or a foreigner proves their identity according to a special legal regulation;^3)

- hh) the „competent district authority“ is the district authority that is competent according to the place of permanent residence of the applicant for a driving license, the applicant for the return of a driving license, the holder of a driving license, or the holder of a driver's license, or, if it concerns a person who does not have permanent residence in the territory of the Czech Republic, with whom the applicant for a driving license, the applicant for the return of a driving license, the holder of a driving license, or the holder of a driver's license passed the professional competence examination according to a special legal regulation;^4)

- ii) a „restraint system“ is a device for ensuring special safety of transported persons, such as a two-point seat belt or a child car seat, approved according to a special legal regulation,^2) replacing the function of a seat belt.

p4.text:
When participating in road traffic, everyone is obliged to:

- a) behave considerately and disciplined, so as not to endanger the life, health, or property of other persons or their own, not to damage the environment, or endanger the lives of animals; their behaviour must be adapted in particular to the structural and traffic-technical condition of the road,^1) weather conditions, the traffic situation on the road, their abilities, and their health condition;

- b) comply with the road traffic rules regulated by this Act, instructions of a police officer, instructions of persons authorised to direct road traffic pursuant to § 75 para. 5 and to stop vehicles pursuant to § 79 para. 1, and instructions of persons specified by a special legal regulation,^5) issued to ensure the safety and smooth flow of road traffic;

- c) comply with light signals, and possibly accompanying acoustic signals, traffic signs, traffic devices, and operational information devices.

p7.text:
(1) The driver must not:

- a) hand over the driving of a motor vehicle to a person who does not meet the conditions of § 3 para. 3;

- b) disturb other road users or other persons, especially by excessive noise, air pollution, splashing puddles, mud, or unnecessarily leaving the engine of a stationary vehicle running;

- c) hold a telephone or other communication device in hand while driving a vehicle;

- d) smoke while riding a motorcycle, moped, or bicycle;

- e) transport a person under 12 years of age on the second seat of a motorcycle.

(2) The driver of a public transport vehicle must not smoke in the vehicle, eat or drink while driving, talk to passengers, allow them into the space reserved for the driver, start moving before the doors are closed, or open the doors before stopping.

(3) The driver of a taxi service vehicle and occasional passenger road transport^10) must not smoke in the vehicle when transporting persons.

(4) The driver of a motor vehicle with a maximum permissible weight exceeding 3,500 kg, a special vehicle, or a combination of vehicles must drive downhill with a gear engaged. The driver of a motor vehicle with a maximum permissible weight not exceeding 3,500 kg must do so if driving safety requires it.

p29.text:
(1) The driver must not enter a railway crossing:

- a) if a warning is given by two red alternately flashing lights of the railway crossing safety device signal;

- b) if a warning is given by an intermittent sound of a horn or bell of the railway crossing safety device;

- c) if barriers are lowering, are lowered, or are rising;

- d) if an approaching train or other rail vehicle is already visible or audible, or if its horn or whistle is audible; this does not apply if the intermittent white light of the railway crossing safety device signal is illuminated;

- e) if a railway employee gives a signal to stop the vehicle by circling a red or yellow flag, and in reduced visibility by circling a red light;

- f) if the situation beyond the railway crossing does not allow for its safe crossing and continuation of the journey.

(2) In the cases specified in paragraph 1 letters a), b), and c), the driver may enter the railway crossing only if they have received oral consent to cross the railway crossing from an authorized employee of the railway operator^11) before the railway crossing. In this case, the driver is obliged to follow the instructions of the authorized employee of the railway operator when crossing the railway crossing. The authorized employee of the railway operator is obliged to present a valid authorization from the railway operator upon the driver's request.

p63.text:
(1) Vertical traffic signs are:

- a) warning signs, which alert to places where road users are at risk and must exercise increased caution;

- b) priority signs, which establish right-of-way in road traffic;

- c) prohibitory signs, which impose prohibitions or restrictions on road users;

- d) mandatory signs, which impose commands on road users;

- e) informative signs, which provide road users with necessary information, serve for their orientation, or impose duties stipulated by this Act or a special legal regulation;^23)

- f) supplementary plates, which specify, supplement, or limit the meaning of the traffic sign under which they are placed.

(2) The implementing legal regulation shall stipulate the details of the classification of informative signs.

p133.text:
(1) Driving licences granted under the regulations valid until 30 June 1964 shall be valid, upon the effective date of this Act, to the following extent:

- a) a Class I or Class II driver's licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in all groups and subgroups of driving licences;

- b) a Class III driver's licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in all groups and subgroups of driving licences, with the exception of groups D, D + E and subgroups D1 and D1 + E;

- c) a passenger car driver's licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups AM, B and subgroup B1 and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3;

- d) a motorcycle driver's licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups A, AM and subgroup A1;

- e) a tractor driver's licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups AM and T and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3;

- f) a small motorcycle driver's licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence group AM and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3.

(2) Driving licences granted under the regulations valid after 1 July 1964 shall be valid, upon the effective date of this Act, to the following extent:

- a) a Group A driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups A, AM and subgroup A1;

- b) a Group B driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups B, AM and subgroup B1 and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3;

- c) a Group C driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups AM, B, C, T and subgroups B1, C1 and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3;

- d) a Group D driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups AM, B, C, D, T and subgroups B1, C1, D1 and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3;

- e) a Group E driving licence with a Group B driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence group B + E;

- f) a Group E driving licence with a Group C driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence group C + E and subgroup C1 + E;

- g) a Group E driving licence with a Group D driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence group D + E and subgroup D1 + E;

- h) a Group M and A/50 driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence group AM and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3;

- i) a Group T driving licence authorises the driving of motor vehicles included in driving licence groups T and AM and subgroup A1 with a restriction up to 50 cm^3.

(3) Restrictions on driving licences recorded in the driving licence based on regulations valid before the effective date of this Act shall remain valid even after the effective date of this Act.

(4) A certificate of competence to drive a traction vehicle on a trolleybus line^41) issued before the effective date of this Act with a Group C driving licence shall cease to be valid on 31 December 2003.
